SIMPLE: muddle
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Muddle
<hw>Mud"dle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Muddled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Muddling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From
<er>Mud</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make turbid, or muddy, as
water.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He did ill to <qex>muddle</qex> the water.</q>
<rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cloud or stupefy; to render stupid with liquor;
to intoxicate partially.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Epicurus seems to have had brains so <qex>muddled</qex> and
confounded, that he scarce ever kept in the right way.</q>
<rj><qau>Bentley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Often drunk, always <qex>muddled</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To waste or misuse, as one does who is stupid or
intoxicated.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>muddle</qex> it [money] away without method or object,
and without having anything to show for it.</q>
<rj><qau>Hazlitt.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To mix confusedly; to confuse; to make a mess of;
<as>as, to <ex>muddle</ex> matters</as>; also, to perplex; to
mystify.</def> <rj><au>F. W. Newman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muddle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Muddle
<hw>Mud"dle</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To dabble in
mud.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To think and act in a confused, aimless
way.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muddle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Muddle
<hw>Mud"dle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A state of being turbid or
confused; hence, intellectual cloudiness or dullness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We both grub on in a <qex>muddle</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muddlehead</ent>⟦br⟧
